10:03.653 --> 10:05.903
Signore Versace, buona sera.

10:07.123 --> 10:09.903
This is my friend, Andrew.

10:09.909 --> 10:11.992
Hi.

10:11.994 --> 10:15.875
It's good to see you in San Francisco.

10:15.881 --> 10:18.044
Thank you.

10:18.050 --> 10:20.880
♪ Last night a DJ saved my life... ♪

10:20.886 --> 10:22.799
I'm excited to see the opera.
I think it's time

10:22.805 --> 10:24.578
we had a contemporary designer
working on...

10:24.585 --> 10:25.719
Have we met before?

10:25.725 --> 10:27.053
♪ ... with a song ♪

10:27.059 --> 10:30.056
Yes. Lago de Como.

10:30.062 --> 10:31.891
A garden party at your residence.

10:31.897 --> 10:33.727
I was by the shore admiring your view

10:33.733 --> 10:35.015
and we exchanged a few words.

10:35.017 --> 10:39.015
You were most gracious.
Of course, I remember it.

10:39.021 --> 10:41.151
But for you to remember it,
it's very flattering.

10:41.157 --> 10:43.737
Yeah, Lago de Como, that must be it.

10:43.743 --> 10:45.155
Yes. So...

10:45.161 --> 10:47.774
Yes... (CONTINUES CHATTING)

10:47.780 --> 10:49.395
My mother's parents are from Italy.

10:49.402 --> 10:52.866
From the south. Schillaci is their
family name. Maybe you know them.

10:52.868 --> 10:55.031
My mother still feels
a very strong connection

10:55.037 --> 10:56.916
to the country, but in truth,
she's never been.

10:56.922 --> 10:58.785
Can you believe that?

10:58.791 --> 11:01.875
An Italian-American that's never
even seen her own country?

11:01.877 --> 11:05.202
♪ 'Cause away goes troubles ♪

11:05.209 --> 11:07.715
♪ Down the drain... ♪

11:07.973 --> 11:09.973
She never returned with you?

11:11.588 --> 11:13.767
Honestly,

11:14.494 --> 11:16.052
I think she's scared.

11:16.725 --> 11:18.084
It's almost as if...

11:18.614 --> 11:24.647
she wants to keep Italy only in
her mind as this perfect place.

11:25.074 --> 11:27.487
♪ Well, all right ♪

11:27.494 --> 11:29.490
(WHISPERS INDISTINCTLY)

11:30.113 --> 11:31.996
Where were her parents born?

11:35.097 --> 11:36.581
Palermo.

11:37.663 --> 11:39.746
Uh, they were born in Palermo.

11:39.748 --> 11:41.748
I'll have whatever he's having.

11:41.750 --> 11:42.988
♪ ... from a broken heart ♪

11:42.995 --> 11:44.053
Sparkling water.

11:44.060 --> 11:45.901
♪ Last night a DJ saved my life ♪

11:45.908 --> 11:47.264
- Palermo, you said.
- Oh, yes.

11:47.271 --> 11:49.413
They moved to Ohio in 1928.

11:50.013 --> 11:53.181
I used to take the ferry to
Palermo when I was a young boy.

11:53.191 --> 11:55.639
ANDREW: So there I am
sitting in the VIP area...

11:55.646 --> 11:57.474
LIZZIE: Wait, where is this?
Hey, do you want some coffee?

11:57.481 --> 11:59.704
Oh, no, I'll get it. So,
sitting in the VIP area

11:59.711 --> 12:01.415
at a private members only club...

12:01.422 --> 12:04.079
Cigars, velvet upholstery...

12:04.086 --> 12:06.132
Very strict policy on
not approaching celebrities,

12:06.139 --> 12:08.135
which I would never do, by the way. Ugh.

12:08.265 --> 12:09.445
So tacky.

12:09.452 --> 12:11.331
So I'm talking with my friend
and then this...

12:11.337 --> 12:13.117
agreeable looking man comes up to me

12:13.123 --> 12:16.453
and he introduces himself as Versace.

12:16.459 --> 12:18.122
Yes. I say to him,

12:18.128 --> 12:20.882
"Honey, if you're Versace,
I'm Coco Chanel."

12:20.889 --> 12:22.068
- No, you didn't.
- I said that.

12:22.075 --> 12:24.132
It's so embarrassing.
And I had to make it up to him

12:24.134 --> 12:25.379
later, when he actually did

12:25.385 --> 12:27.540
establish himself as...

12:28.005 --> 12:29.250
you know, Versace.

12:30.212 --> 12:32.102
I'm not really a fan of his clothes,

12:32.108 --> 12:34.354
per se, it's just so... bright.

12:34.360 --> 12:35.472
It's too much,

12:35.478 --> 12:37.107
- but they say...
- (MOUTHS)

12:37.113 --> 12:39.059
...that Armani
designs clothes for wives.

12:39.065 --> 12:41.445
I think that Versace
designs clothes for sluts,

12:41.451 --> 12:44.031
and don't you look at me like that.

12:44.037 --> 12:46.320
Please, I know the score.

12:46.322 --> 12:48.368
There's a lecherous fag on the prowl.

12:48.374 --> 12:52.305
- I didn't know he was gay.
- Hey, faggot is not a nice word.

12:52.312 --> 12:54.207
ANDREW: Not nice when
it's said by the wrong person.

12:54.214 --> 12:56.326
But what are we supposed to call them?

12:56.332 --> 12:59.683
Homosexuals? Hmm?
Sounds so... scientific.

12:59.690 --> 13:02.299
Anyway, I don't have a problem
with it; it doesn't bother me.

13:02.305 --> 13:04.005
At all. Which is why I agreed.

13:04.007 --> 13:05.339
Wait, you agreed to what?

13:05.341 --> 13:07.971
Oh, didn't I say?

13:07.977 --> 13:09.223
He invited me to the opera.

13:09.229 --> 13:12.009
He's designing the costumes
for Capriccio.

13:12.015 --> 13:13.347
It's a minor work, but even so.

13:13.349 --> 13:17.431
I guess even in minor works,
one must wear clothes.

13:17.437 --> 13:20.100
(MOUTHS) And you said yes?

13:20.106 --> 13:22.240
My dear, sweet Lizzie.

13:26.112 --> 13:30.327
Versace has invited me to the opera.

13:30.333 --> 13:32.246
Of course I said yes.

13:32.252 --> 13:33.413
ANDREW: So I said,

13:33.419 --> 13:35.282
"Lizzie, I'm not crazy about Versace,

13:35.288 --> 13:37.284
but I certainly wouldn't mind
going to the opera."

13:37.290 --> 13:39.286
- Is it real?
- What?

13:39.292 --> 13:41.455
Versace.

13:41.461 --> 13:43.123
What do you mean?

13:43.129 --> 13:45.292
The other day I heard you say
you were half Jewish.

13:45.298 --> 13:48.212
Well... that's complicated.

13:48.218 --> 13:51.014
No, it isn't. You're not Jewish,
you're Catholic, same as me.

13:51.020 --> 13:52.382
You were an altar boy.

13:52.388 --> 13:54.674
(QUIETLY): I mean, we spoke
about what happened to you.

13:54.681 --> 13:56.390
(SCOFFS) What does it matter
what I said?

13:56.392 --> 13:58.305
What does it matter?
It matters. -Yes.

13:58.311 --> 13:59.940
Only if they know it isn't true.

13:59.946 --> 14:01.028
But you know.

14:02.398 --> 14:04.111
I thought you'd be happy about it.

14:04.117 --> 14:05.312
- About what?
- About Versace.

14:05.318 --> 14:06.975
That you'd brag about a date
with Versace?

14:06.982 --> 14:09.680
- It's not a brag.
- You can't even tell people you're gay.

14:09.687 --> 14:12.119
I tell people all the time.
I've told people for years. I...

14:12.125 --> 14:15.126
You tell gay people you're gay and
straight people you're straight.

14:16.963 --> 14:18.996
I tell people what they need to hear.

14:21.084 --> 14:22.329
How am I supposed to behave?

14:22.335 --> 14:26.133
Do I pretend to know the person
you're pretending to be?

14:26.139 --> 14:27.968
I can't keep up.

14:27.974 --> 14:29.970
Every time I feel like
I'm getting close to you,

14:29.976 --> 14:32.059
you say you're someone else.

14:33.313 --> 14:36.176
I know I'm not...

14:36.182 --> 14:38.262
- impressive.
- Okay.

14:38.268 --> 14:39.396
But I'm nice.

14:39.402 --> 14:41.181
I'm smart.

14:41.187 --> 14:44.272
And I'm kind.

14:44.274 --> 14:47.441
ANDREW: I (SCOFFS) honestly...

14:49.996 --> 14:52.079
Truthfully.

14:54.083 --> 14:57.368
I swear, I really do have
a date with Gianni Versace.

14:59.956 --> 15:02.123
I'm pleased for you.

15:04.177 --> 15:05.293
Good.

15:35.158 --> 15:37.291
♪ ♪

15:47.112 --> 15:48.204
(DOOR OPENS)

16:01.414 --> 16:03.604
VERSACE: What? No, no, no,
darling, look at yourself.

16:03.611 --> 16:05.533
Look at yourself in the mirror.
Don't look at me.

16:05.540 --> 16:06.878
In the mirror.

16:07.807 --> 16:11.059
To adjust a dress,
the most important thing

16:11.703 --> 16:13.861
is that I look at your face.

16:14.260 --> 16:16.206
It's that I see your face.

16:16.212 --> 16:17.699
I learned that from my mother.

16:18.012 --> 16:19.178
She was a dressmaker.

16:19.180 --> 16:20.964
She had a little store in Calabria.

16:21.557 --> 16:24.825
My mother, she would stand
with her clients...

16:24.832 --> 16:26.282
Who she considered her friends...

16:26.289 --> 16:30.114
In front of the mirror
and study their expressions.

16:30.191 --> 16:33.238
Not the fabric, not the dress.

16:33.244 --> 16:36.107
Their faces and only when
they were happy,

16:36.113 --> 16:40.387
only when they smile, when they relax,

16:40.394 --> 16:42.078
her work was complete.

16:42.642 --> 16:45.199
My clothes serve you, darling.

16:45.206 --> 16:47.206
I work for you. I'm not important.

16:47.208 --> 16:49.439
It's you, it's all about you. Yes?

16:50.044 --> 16:51.587
- Mm, yes.
- Now you go.

16:52.203 --> 16:54.959
("ALL AROUND THE WORLD"
BY LISA STANSFIELD PLAYING)

16:54.965 --> 16:57.216
♪ Been around the world and I-I-I ♪

16:57.218 --> 16:59.264
♪ I can't find my baby ♪

16:59.270 --> 17:01.349
♪ I don't know when, I don't know why ♪

17:01.355 --> 17:04.056
♪ Why he's gone away ♪

17:04.058 --> 17:09.057
♪ And I don't know ♪
♪ where he can be, my baby ♪

17:09.063 --> 17:11.230
- ♪ But I'm gonna find him ♪
- (LIZZIE SIGHS)

17:13.117 --> 17:15.233
You should have asked.

17:16.342 --> 17:18.887
♪ And I let myself go ♪

17:18.895 --> 17:22.287
♪ I said so many things,
things he didn't know... ♪

17:22.292 --> 17:25.290
I have nothing.

17:25.296 --> 17:28.450
♪ I don't think he's coming back... ♪

17:28.457 --> 17:30.295
You look very nice.

17:30.301 --> 17:31.664
"Nice."

17:32.136 --> 17:33.331
What were you going for?

17:33.337 --> 17:36.167
Im-pressive.

17:36.173 --> 17:38.420
♪ ... the reasons he should go ♪

17:38.426 --> 17:42.257
♪ And he said things
he hasn't said before ♪

17:42.263 --> 17:45.060
♪ And he was oh, oh, so mad ♪

17:45.066 --> 17:46.789
♪ And I don't think... ♪

17:46.796 --> 17:47.890
Give me your hand.

17:49.085 --> 17:51.266
♪ Coming back ♪

17:51.272 --> 17:53.268
Mm-hmm.

17:53.274 --> 17:55.236
You should... no. Uh...

17:55.242 --> 17:57.238
♪ Wasted too much time ♪

17:57.244 --> 17:59.278
♪ Now I'm here a'crying... ♪

17:59.280 --> 18:01.192
I love you.

18:01.198 --> 18:03.282
You are ridiculous.

18:05.286 --> 18:07.082
See, that's impressive.

18:07.088 --> 18:08.148
Yes.

18:08.155 --> 18:11.655
(CLOCK CHIMING)

18:12.293 --> 18:14.093
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

18:16.931 --> 18:19.932
(CLOCK CONTINUES CHIMING)

18:25.973 --> 18:27.940
♪ ♪

18:32.154 --> 18:34.980
(WOMAN SINGING IN ITALIAN)

18:44.158 --> 18:46.125
♪ ♪

19:12.903 --> 19:14.853
♪ ♪

19:40.264 --> 19:42.214
♪ ♪

19:54.311 --> 19:57.279
(WOMAN HOLDING FINAL NOTE)

20:17.051 --> 20:18.300
(TINKLES)

20:44.411 --> 20:46.107
(SIGHS)

20:46.113 --> 20:47.275
Did you enjoy?

20:47.281 --> 20:49.281
I loved it.

20:49.283 --> 20:52.413
I thought it was inspiring.

20:52.419 --> 20:54.365
You are creative, right?

20:54.371 --> 20:56.334
Oh, pfft, of course, very much.

20:56.340 --> 20:57.413
Thank you.

20:57.420 --> 20:58.422
(GLASSES CLINK)

21:02.011 --> 21:04.091
What do you do for work?

21:04.098 --> 21:06.427
This and that. And for my first job,

21:06.433 --> 21:10.181
I worked for my father
on his pineapple plantations

21:10.187 --> 21:12.016
in the Philippines...
Can you imagine that?

21:12.022 --> 21:14.385
Picking them in the midday sun.
You should've seen me.

21:14.391 --> 21:16.814
My father was a-a military man.

21:16.821 --> 21:19.772
He was a pilot for Imelda Marcos,

21:19.779 --> 21:21.818
- The First Lady of the Philippines.
- Really?

21:21.825 --> 21:24.028
Yes. He flew one of those old planes,

21:24.034 --> 21:26.197
the, um, the type
that Buddy Holly died in.

21:26.203 --> 21:28.449
Beechcraft Bonanza, they're
called, if you know them.

21:28.455 --> 21:30.368
He would fly them
low to the ground because

21:30.374 --> 21:31.990
Imelda was terrified of crashing,

21:31.992 --> 21:33.037
and that is a true story.

21:33.043 --> 21:34.372
My father would tell her,

21:34.378 --> 21:36.995
"Imelda, when you're flying a plane"

21:36.997 --> 21:40.078
at 400 miles per hour
in a rickety tin can,

21:40.084 --> 21:42.463
"it doesn't, it doesn't matter
how high you are."

21:42.469 --> 21:44.165
(CHUCKLES)

21:44.171 --> 21:46.171
And then you moved to America.

21:46.173 --> 21:49.220
My father wanted me to have
the very best education.

21:49.226 --> 21:52.056
Which, of course, I had.

21:52.062 --> 21:53.474
He's retired from the military now.

21:53.480 --> 21:57.178
He runs all of his businesses
from abroad, 'cause he can.

21:57.184 --> 22:00.231
Who knew that there was so much
money to be made in pineapples?

22:00.237 --> 22:02.266
He was here the other day,
he was just in town.

22:02.272 --> 22:05.103
He was driving around in his Rolls-Royce

22:05.109 --> 22:08.360
with his boyfriend as a chauffeur.

22:08.362 --> 22:09.406
Boyfriend?

22:09.413 --> 22:11.485
- Please, don't ask.
- Your father has a boyfriend?

22:11.492 --> 22:13.548
He left my mom and ran off
with one of the young men

22:13.555 --> 22:15.192
who worked on the plantations.

22:17.087 --> 22:19.167
It was cute, I guess.

22:19.173 --> 22:21.039
It's all so crazy.

22:21.041 --> 22:22.207
I'm writing a novel about it.

22:22.209 --> 22:24.042
- You are?
- Mm-hmm.

22:24.044 --> 22:26.061
I wish I had the patience
to write a novel.

22:26.068 --> 22:28.960
But my mind is always moving, you know?

22:28.966 --> 22:31.963
I think you need great stillness
to write a novel.

22:31.969 --> 22:34.298
And I'm never still.

22:34.304 --> 22:37.135
Maybe you just need a crazy family.

22:37.141 --> 22:38.970
For me, family's everything.

22:38.976 --> 22:40.225
- Everything.
- Hmm.

22:40.227 --> 22:42.974
The first dress I ever made
was for my sister Donatella.

22:42.980 --> 22:45.063
Maybe every dress I make is for her.

22:46.283 --> 22:48.229
That makes me want to cry.

22:48.235 --> 22:50.031
Makes me smile.

22:50.037 --> 22:52.404
Uh, yes, well, that, too.
Yeah, of course.

22:54.408 --> 22:58.072
The Medusa logo, from my company...

22:58.078 --> 22:59.207
You know it?

22:59.213 --> 23:01.042
So sophisticated.

23:01.048 --> 23:04.962
As children, we used to play
in ancient ruins

23:04.968 --> 23:08.049
close to our home in Calabria.

23:08.055 --> 23:10.968
And one day, I saw
the Medusa's head with the...

23:10.974 --> 23:13.388
hair of snakes carved on
the stone and I fell in love.

23:13.394 --> 23:16.307
I know that many people call it
pretentious, but I don't care.

23:16.314 --> 23:18.519
How could my childhood be pretentious?

23:18.526 --> 23:19.588
I agree.

23:19.595 --> 23:21.095
My hope is that when people...

23:21.101 --> 23:22.882
- wear my clothes,
- (LIQUID POURS)

23:22.889 --> 23:24.852
they will get to know me
a little bit, you know?

23:24.859 --> 23:28.436
They will get to know my
character, my-my love for life.

23:28.442 --> 23:32.190
And I think that the same
will happen with your novel.

23:32.196 --> 23:34.976
People will get to know you a little
bit when they read your book.

23:34.982 --> 23:37.245
- I'll send you an advanced copy.
- (GLASSES CLINK)

23:37.251 --> 23:39.113
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

23:39.119 --> 23:41.332
You think I should change my name

23:41.338 --> 23:42.954
to something a little more literary?

23:42.956 --> 23:45.119
I was, I was thinking Andrew DeSilva.

23:45.125 --> 23:47.092
No. You should be proud of your name.

23:49.129 --> 23:51.008
When they make a movie of my book,

23:51.014 --> 23:53.294
you must design the clothes.
You have to.

23:53.300 --> 23:55.158
You... for Imelda, think of it.

23:55.165 --> 23:56.861
She was a fashion icon,
it'll be perfect.

23:56.868 --> 23:58.363
You know she had 3,000 pairs of shoes.

23:58.370 --> 23:59.984
I know, but I don't design shoes.

23:59.990 --> 24:01.135
Well...

24:01.141 --> 24:04.109
But maybe I could try, for your movie.

24:06.146 --> 24:08.159
Hmm?

24:08.165 --> 24:10.982
Maybe.

24:10.984 --> 24:13.030
I'm so happy right now.

24:13.036 --> 24:14.949
You should be.

24:14.955 --> 24:18.990
You're handsome, clever.

24:21.962 --> 24:25.330
I'm sure...

24:25.332 --> 24:28.917
you're going to be someone
really special one day.

24:30.971 --> 24:32.921
(GUNSHOT ECHOES)

24:39.980 --> 24:41.313
(GUNSHOT)

24:42.349 --> 24:45.934
(BIRD COOING)

24:53.277 --> 24:55.410
(WAVES CRASHING)

24:58.165 --> 25:00.332
(RUNNING FOOTSTEPS)

25:05.205 --> 25:07.172
Hey!

25:08.375 --> 25:09.958
Hey!

25:15.815 --> 25:17.362
Gianni.

25:17.955 --> 25:19.125
Help!

25:24.141 --> 25:25.190
(GUN COCKS)

25:35.319 --> 25:37.365
(SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE)

25:37.371 --> 25:39.137
(SIREN WAILING)

25:40.240 --> 25:42.153
(TIRES SCREECH, SIREN STOPS)

25:42.159 --> 25:43.408
ANTONIO: Help!

25:43.410 --> 25:45.410
Please help.

25:45.412 --> 25:47.241
I just need an ambulance.

25:47.247 --> 25:48.964
Get an ambulance.

26:08.101 --> 26:10.268
(PANTING)

26:30.007 --> 26:32.336
Ah...

26:32.342 --> 26:34.926
(LAUGHS)

26:38.131 --> 26:40.215
Yes!

26:42.302 --> 26:45.383
(MUTTERS)

26:45.389 --> 26:48.281
Ha! (LAUGHS)

26:51.028 --> 26:53.278
(SOBBING)

26:55.365 --> 26:57.232
(SIGHS HEAVILY)

27:02.072 --> 27:04.235
(GROANS)

27:04.241 --> 27:06.241
(SIRENS WAILING)

27:20.655 --> 27:22.901
(SIREN WAILS, STOPS)

27:22.907 --> 27:25.575
(INDISTINCT POLICE RADIO CHATTER)

27:28.731 --> 27:30.613
- You know who that is?
- No.

27:32.735 --> 27:34.402
It's Gianni Versace.

27:35.571 --> 27:36.746
ANTONIO: Ambulance...

27:37.596 --> 27:40.011
(SOBBING):
Where's the ambulance? Please.

27:40.264 --> 27:43.348
- Jesus.
- Please help!

27:43.779 --> 27:45.779
Move! Get an ambulance!

27:45.781 --> 27:46.830
(SIREN WAILING)

27:56.759 --> 27:57.791
Yes!

28:09.939 --> 28:11.050
Here we go.

28:11.056 --> 28:13.052
(SIGHS) All right.

28:13.058 --> 28:15.726
(INDISTINCT POLICE RADIO CHATTER)

28:20.950 --> 28:22.816
(STRETCHER ROLLING AWAY)

28:28.958 --> 28:30.741
Hey, stop!

28:33.996 --> 28:36.288
DISPATCHER: All units, suspect last seen

28:36.295 --> 28:38.828
entering 13th Street garage
wearing red baseball hat,

28:38.834 --> 28:40.797
gray T-shirt. Please advise.

28:40.803 --> 28:42.669
No red hat, but some guy in a red shirt.

28:42.676 --> 28:45.192
Latino. A security guard
or parking attendant.

28:45.199 --> 28:47.199
- I'll check him out.
- (SIREN WAILING)

28:48.844 --> 28:50.761
(SIREN WAILING)

28:53.983 --> 28:55.015
(TIRES SCREECH)

28:56.685 --> 28:57.985
(REPORTERS CLAMORING)

29:02.691 --> 29:04.024
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

29:06.362 --> 29:08.775
- NURSE: What do we got?
- PARAMEDIC: Patient has GSW

29:08.781 --> 29:10.827
times two to the head,
found in cardiac arrest.

29:10.833 --> 29:12.829
Asystolic, pupils are fixed and dilated.

29:12.835 --> 29:14.304
SURGEON: How long has he been down?

29:14.311 --> 29:16.110
- We're in.
- Get him to Trauma One.

29:19.792 --> 29:21.754
OFFICER: Hey, you!

29:21.760 --> 29:23.623
Stop right there!

29:23.629 --> 29:25.041
OFFICER 2: Freeze!

29:25.047 --> 29:26.096
OFFICER 3: Freeze!

29:27.621 --> 29:29.536
Freeze!
Freeze, right there!

29:29.543 --> 29:31.547
- Come on, people. Let's go.
- Keep him centered.

29:31.554 --> 29:33.515
- Push, push.
- Coming through, coming through.

29:33.522 --> 29:34.817
I need that pulse.

29:34.819 --> 29:36.769
NURSE: GCS, level 3.

29:36.775 --> 29:39.689
(ALL CHATTERING EXCITEDLY)

29:39.695 --> 29:42.025
Suspect on the run, in pursuit!

29:42.031 --> 29:43.730
Española Way.

29:43.732 --> 29:44.865
Heading east.

29:49.872 --> 29:51.034
Suspect is down.

29:51.040 --> 29:52.823
- (SHOUTS)
- Turn him over!

30:00.916 --> 30:02.829
Let's go, let's go, let's go!

30:02.835 --> 30:04.656
NURSE: We need a crash cart.

30:04.663 --> 30:06.494
- Get a cart, get a cart.
- SURGEON: On three.

30:06.501 --> 30:08.870
- One, two, three. Lift.
- (ALL GRUNT)

30:08.877 --> 30:10.140
Attempting CPR.

30:12.728 --> 30:13.840
NURSE: Get a second line.

30:13.846 --> 30:15.145
SURGEON: Come on.

30:17.850 --> 30:20.934
I have a weak pulse.

30:20.936 --> 30:23.690
- Let's go, people, we've got a pulse.
- Let's prep him for x-ray.

30:23.697 --> 30:25.155
(CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)

30:26.942 --> 30:29.739
Hey, guys. I-I have the only photo.

30:29.745 --> 30:31.099
The only...

30:31.707 --> 30:33.900
I have the only photo of Versace.

30:34.750 --> 30:37.030
Bidding starts at $30,000.

30:37.036 --> 30:40.049
Looks like the bullet entered the
maxilla and lodged in the vertex.

30:40.055 --> 30:42.201
- Tore through the parietal lobe.
- Not operable.

30:42.207 --> 30:44.124
(MONITOR BEEPING RHYTHMICALLY)

30:52.217 --> 30:54.847
(MONITOR FLATLINES)

30:54.853 --> 30:55.969
Hold CPR.

31:03.145 --> 31:05.812
Call it.

31:05.814 --> 31:08.982
TIME OF DEATH: 9:21 a.m.

31:33.058 --> 31:35.008
♪ ♪

31:39.014 --> 31:43.733
(WOMAN SINGING VINCENZO
BELLINI'S "OH! QUANTE VOLTE")

31:48.941 --> 31:50.907
♪ ♪

32:10.045 --> 32:12.712
♪ ♪

32:15.851 --> 32:17.210
Who is he?

32:17.733 --> 32:19.052
Boyfriend.

32:22.724 --> 32:24.691
♪ ♪

32:32.034 --> 32:33.980
MAN: Go, go, go, go, go, go.

32:33.986 --> 32:35.982
OFFICER: Stay behind the line.

32:35.988 --> 32:38.155
♪ ♪

32:41.910 --> 32:44.161
OFFICER: Hey! You want to be arrested?

32:47.082 --> 32:49.916
♪ ♪

33:03.098 --> 33:05.065
♪ ♪

33:15.944 --> 33:17.944
♪ ♪

33:35.881 --> 33:37.847
♪ ♪

33:42.313 --> 33:44.480
(INHALES DEEPLY)

33:45.974 --> 33:47.107
(CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)

33:51.813 --> 33:53.813
MALE NEWS REPORTER:
Breaking news from Miami Beach.

33:53.815 --> 33:55.380
We've received reports of a shooting

33:55.387 --> 33:57.813
at fashion designer
Gianni Versace's mansion

33:57.819 --> 33:58.985
on Ocean Drive.

33:58.987 --> 34:00.950
The shooting occurred
this morning at 9:00 a.m.

34:00.956 --> 34:03.786
No official statement
from police has been made,

34:03.792 --> 34:06.989
but the investigation
is ongoing at this time.

34:06.995 --> 34:08.791
Eyewitnesses have confirmed
there is at least

34:08.797 --> 34:10.960
one victim who was shot
and rushed to the hospital.

34:10.966 --> 34:13.245
Our reporter is standing by.

34:13.252 --> 34:14.996
Well, we have just arrived at the scene,

34:15.003 --> 34:16.554
but we can confirm

34:16.562 --> 34:20.001
that world-famous
fashion designer Gianni Versace

34:20.007 --> 34:23.139
has been shot here on the steps
outside his villa.

34:23.145 --> 34:25.841
(REPORT CONTINUES INDISTINCTLY)

34:25.847 --> 34:28.014
♪ ♪

34:49.429 --> 34:50.592
OFFICER: South Carolina tags.

34:50.599 --> 34:53.326
Sam-King-William-2-6-3.

34:53.333 --> 34:55.550
(INDISTINCT CHATTER OVER RADIO)

34:57.623 --> 34:59.502
Nah, nothing's coming up.

34:59.509 --> 35:00.825
Could be stolen plates.

35:00.832 --> 35:02.261
Try the vehicle I.D. number.

35:02.268 --> 35:04.552
FEMALE OFFICER: King-1-Adam-1-0.

35:08.467 --> 35:11.827
Yeah. Vehicle linked to
the homicide of William Reese.

35:11.834 --> 35:14.801
Suspect name is Andrew Cunanan.

35:16.906 --> 35:19.470
FBI AGENT: Pronounced Ver-sash-shay.

35:19.477 --> 35:20.796
FBI AGENT 2: Singer?

35:21.632 --> 35:23.010
That's Liberace.

35:23.012 --> 35:25.229
It's the jeans guy.

35:27.071 --> 35:28.733
FBI AGENT 1: Listen up, everyone.

35:28.740 --> 35:30.145
Who do we have in Miami?

35:30.152 --> 35:32.936
- (SIREN WAILING)
- (PEOPLE CHATTERING)

35:35.157 --> 35:37.074
(SIREN CHIRPS, STOPS)

35:52.187 --> 35:53.791
You heard about the Chevy?

35:53.798 --> 35:55.465
SCRIMSHAW: Red Chevy 1500.

35:55.472 --> 35:57.090
- Pickup truck?
- That's right.

35:57.096 --> 35:58.791
Hot damn, that's Cunanan.

35:58.797 --> 36:00.843
That's Andrew Cunanan.

36:00.849 --> 36:03.796
Agent Evans has been looking
for Cunanan for several months.

36:03.802 --> 36:05.098
In Miami?

36:05.104 --> 36:07.133
In Fort Lauderdale, too.

36:07.139 --> 36:08.722
NAVARRO: Who is he?

36:12.895 --> 36:15.062
How many people has he killed?

36:15.064 --> 36:18.061
Four. Five now with... Versace.

36:18.067 --> 36:19.866
How many flyers have gone out?

36:21.237 --> 36:23.153
How many have gone out, Agent Evans?

36:30.246 --> 36:32.212
(CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)

36:34.659 --> 36:36.162
BARETTO: Shortly before 9:00 a.m.,

36:36.168 --> 36:38.998
fashion designer Gianni Versace

36:39.004 --> 36:41.084
was shot on the steps of his villa.

36:41.090 --> 36:44.091
He was then taken
to Jackson Memorial Hospital,

36:44.093 --> 36:47.144
where he was pronounced dead
at 9:21 a.m.

37:10.919 --> 37:12.949
Miami Beach Police investigators,

37:12.955 --> 37:15.956
in cooperation with the Federal
Bureau of Investigation,

37:15.958 --> 37:17.920
and the Florida Department
of Law Enforcement,

37:17.926 --> 37:20.873
are currently looking for
Andrew Phillip Cunanan

37:20.879 --> 37:23.213
as a suspect in the murder
of Gianni Versace.

37:37.229 --> 37:39.942
Cunanan should be considered

37:39.948 --> 37:42.816
armed and extremely dangerous
at this time.

37:44.870 --> 37:47.037
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)
- (CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)

37:48.157 --> 37:51.124
(CROWD CLAMORING OUTSIDE)

38:11.847 --> 38:13.013
(CROWD CLAMORING)

38:16.935 --> 38:18.935
(CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)

38:57.810 --> 39:01.042
SCRIMSHAW: What was your
involvement with Mr. Versace?

39:02.035 --> 39:03.230
ANTONIO: My involvement?

39:03.232 --> 39:06.813
You were the person who found
these, uh, dancers, models,

39:06.819 --> 39:08.948
escorts, and brought them back
to the house for sex?

39:08.954 --> 39:10.983
Who told you that?

39:10.989 --> 39:13.069
Mr. D'Amico, this is
a police investigation.

39:13.075 --> 39:14.855
We need to know everything.

39:14.862 --> 39:16.919
The staff told me
when I interviewed them.

39:17.489 --> 39:19.913
Well, I was his partner, not his pimp.

39:19.915 --> 39:22.484
By partner, you mean...?

39:22.491 --> 39:24.217
What-what do I mean?

39:30.636 --> 39:32.035
(NAVARRO CLEARS THROAT)

39:34.265 --> 39:36.175
Hey. Listen, I'm...

39:36.181 --> 39:38.060
I'm on your side.

39:38.677 --> 39:42.215
I'm just trying to figure out
what was going on at the house.

39:42.446 --> 39:44.645
Now, you say you're partners.

39:44.652 --> 39:45.754
Partner.

39:47.592 --> 39:49.038
His companion.

39:50.342 --> 39:51.891
I loved him.

39:51.898 --> 39:54.243
Though you were, um,
bringing back other men?

39:54.249 --> 39:55.912
For him?

39:55.918 --> 39:58.952
You were... having sex with them, too?

39:58.954 --> 40:00.166
With him there?

40:00.717 --> 40:02.251
Sometimes.

40:03.165 --> 40:05.799
Sometimes he wouldn't join in?

40:05.844 --> 40:07.290
(SCOFFS)

40:07.296 --> 40:09.175
No, not always.

40:09.489 --> 40:11.059
Sometimes...

40:11.879 --> 40:14.046
it was, it was whatever he wanted.

40:14.052 --> 40:17.133
These other men, uh,
did they consider themselves

40:17.139 --> 40:19.268
to be Versace's partner, too?

40:19.274 --> 40:21.103
- No. Of course...
- You see why I'm confused?

40:21.109 --> 40:22.138
What's the difference?

40:22.865 --> 40:24.273
15 years.

40:24.903 --> 40:27.309
I lived with Gianni for 15
years, that is the difference.

40:27.316 --> 40:28.945
Okay. That-that's, um...

40:28.951 --> 40:31.234
(SNIFFS) that's a good length of time.

40:33.038 --> 40:35.201
Could you give us their names?
These other men.

40:35.207 --> 40:37.123
I can, I can find out.

40:38.961 --> 40:40.323
Were they paid?

40:40.329 --> 40:42.829
Oh, yes, no.

40:42.831 --> 40:44.994
Most of the time they just fell for him.

40:45.000 --> 40:47.330
He was a genius.

40:47.946 --> 40:49.215
He cast a spell.

40:49.221 --> 40:51.838
Hmm. Were you paid?

40:51.840 --> 40:53.302
Was I paid?

40:53.308 --> 40:55.888
To love him?! Was I paid to love him?

40:55.894 --> 40:56.923
I'm sorry.

40:56.929 --> 40:58.808
I know you're upset, but...

40:58.814 --> 41:01.928
this is new to me, I'm just
trying to get everything clear.

41:01.934 --> 41:05.018
- Don't want to make presumptions.
- Yes, and I'm trying to help, but...

41:08.991 --> 41:12.188
Did you see the man who shot Versace?

41:12.194 --> 41:13.940
No.

41:13.946 --> 41:17.113
Well, might it be one
of these men who killed him?

41:21.253 --> 41:23.870
(DOOR OPENS)

41:42.220 --> 41:44.281
Get them out, please.

41:47.062 --> 41:48.945
(INDISTINCT POLICE RADIO CHATTER)

42:01.126 --> 42:03.789
(SOBBING)

42:03.795 --> 42:05.745
That's not what I need
from you right now.

42:09.918 --> 42:11.801
What do you need from me?

42:12.971 --> 42:15.251
What were you saying to the police?

42:15.257 --> 42:18.018
I don't know, they were
asking some questions.

42:19.101 --> 42:20.905
About Gianni's life.

42:21.930 --> 42:24.064
What about my brother's life?

42:29.021 --> 42:30.900
They will find out, Donatella.

42:30.906 --> 42:33.903
What? What will they find out?

42:33.909 --> 42:35.382
Everything.

42:35.859 --> 42:36.993
(SCOFFS)

42:38.897 --> 42:41.027
Nothing was ever asked of you

42:41.033 --> 42:43.162
except to take care of him.

42:43.168 --> 42:45.081
And you couldn't even do that.

42:51.401 --> 42:53.513
You are not to speak to anyone
about my brother

42:53.520 --> 42:55.553
without consulting me first.

43:15.283 --> 43:16.950
(DOOR CLOSES)

43:28.880 --> 43:30.830
♪ ♪

44:01.029 --> 44:03.079
DONATELLA: Please sit down.

44:04.166 --> 44:05.915
Well...

44:08.954 --> 44:11.033
Thank you for coming.

44:11.039 --> 44:14.170
For me to talk about business
at this time,

44:14.176 --> 44:17.210
it's... kind of crazy, no? (SNIFFLES)

44:22.801 --> 44:26.015
As you know, my brother,

44:26.021 --> 44:29.139
who I love very much, is dead.

44:30.809 --> 44:33.139
And now, the press and the police

44:33.145 --> 44:35.141
will rake through his life.

44:35.147 --> 44:38.144
Every rumor, every indiscretion.

44:38.150 --> 44:40.029
They'll judge the killer, yes,

44:40.035 --> 44:41.951
but they'll judge the victim, too.

44:43.955 --> 44:45.201
At first people weep.

44:45.207 --> 44:47.073
Then they whisper.

44:47.075 --> 44:50.956
(SNIFFLES)

44:50.962 --> 44:55.081
Gianni grew his company
from one small store in Milano.

44:55.083 --> 44:57.880
On Via della Spiga.

44:57.886 --> 45:00.132
With a single rack of clothes,

45:00.138 --> 45:04.804
a little wooden bench,

45:04.810 --> 45:06.839
and a pietra grigia stone floor.

45:06.845 --> 45:08.891
The same stone
that's in our family chapel.

45:08.897 --> 45:11.894
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

45:11.900 --> 45:14.096
Our mother was there, Franca.

45:14.102 --> 45:17.933
She was so proud.

45:17.939 --> 45:20.186
From that to all this.

45:20.192 --> 45:22.271
Everything you see around us.

45:22.277 --> 45:25.024
This house, this company...

45:25.030 --> 45:28.077
He was a creator, he was a collector,

45:28.083 --> 45:29.910
he was a genius.

45:30.786 --> 45:34.116
And this company was his life.

45:34.122 --> 45:36.956
When he was sad, it made him happy.

45:36.958 --> 45:40.840
When he was sick, it kept him alive.

45:40.846 --> 45:44.293
And my brother is still alive,
as long as Versace's alive.

45:44.299 --> 45:47.129
I will not allow that man...

45:47.135 --> 45:51.137
That nobody... to kill my brother twice.

45:54.860 --> 45:56.188
MAN: The family thanks

45:56.194 --> 45:59.145
all those who have paid
their respects...

45:59.147 --> 46:03.062
and marked their grief with silence.

46:03.068 --> 46:06.152
This is a heinous
and inexplicable crime.

46:06.154 --> 46:11.871
Neither Gianni Versace,
nor any of his family,

46:11.877 --> 46:14.828
knew or had any contact

46:14.830 --> 46:18.960
with the suspect
known as Andrew Cunanan.

46:20.257 --> 46:21.914
Thank you very much.

46:21.920 --> 46:24.087
- (REPORTERS CLAMORING)
- (CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)

46:38.858 --> 46:41.718
That was the last night official
statement from the house of Versace.

46:41.733 --> 46:42.901
Lydia's at the scene.

46:42.908 --> 46:45.785
LYDIA: With the death of Gianni
Versace, Miami is now at the center

46:45.787 --> 46:48.534
of one of the largest
FBI manhunts of all time.

46:48.540 --> 46:51.704
The police have named
Andrew Cunanan as the suspect.

46:51.710 --> 46:53.706
MALE REPORTER: Please call
the Channel 15 tip line

46:53.712 --> 46:56.442
if you have any information.
Operators are standing by.

46:56.448 --> 46:59.482
This is a nationwide manhunt.
Be on alert.

47:04.389 --> 47:05.805
(LOCK BUZZES)

47:09.331 --> 47:11.640
I gave him $190 cash for that coin.

47:12.247 --> 47:13.960
Okay, I did everything right.

47:13.966 --> 47:15.411
I did everything by the book.

47:15.417 --> 47:18.810
I asked him for his I.D.,
he gave me a U.S. passport.

47:18.817 --> 47:20.415
Andrew P. Cunanan.

47:20.422 --> 47:22.793
I asked him for his address.

47:22.800 --> 47:25.721
He gave me this address,
right here. Okay?

47:25.728 --> 47:29.096
I handed the paperwork
into you guys, July 7.

47:29.098 --> 47:31.520
Seven days before Versace was shot.

47:31.527 --> 47:33.972
We got an address on Andrew Cunanan.

47:34.436 --> 47:38.101
DONATELLA: Gianni had hoped to
be the first Italian designer

47:38.107 --> 47:41.354
to list his company on both
the Milan Borsa

47:41.360 --> 47:43.356
and the New York Stock Exchange.

47:43.362 --> 47:46.113
The papers with Morgan Stanley
were signed.

47:46.115 --> 47:48.027
They were signed a week ago.

47:48.033 --> 47:50.450
That's why he was here, in this country.

47:50.452 --> 47:54.200
So, I know how much it meant to him.

47:54.206 --> 47:57.036
We can still go ahead.

47:57.042 --> 47:58.338
He would have wanted us to.

47:58.344 --> 48:00.423
Yes, he would have wanted that.

48:00.429 --> 48:02.425
He would have wanted his death
to change nothing,

48:02.431 --> 48:04.427
but it changes everything.

48:04.433 --> 48:06.299
If we pull out,

48:06.301 --> 48:09.432
